[30;1m526 | [0m[35mIf you call `SigningKey.sign_deterministic(data)` instead of `.sign(data)`,[0m
[30;1m527 | [0m[35mthe code will generate a deterministic signature instead of a random one.[0m
[30;1m528 | [0m[35mThis uses the algorithm from RFC6979 to safely generate a unique `k` value,[0m
[30;1m529 | [0m[35mderived from the private key and the message being signed. Each time you sign[0m
[30;1m530 | [0m[35mthe same message with the same key, you will get the same signature (using[0m
[30;1m531 | [0m[35mthe same `k`).[0m
[30;1m532 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m339 | [0m[35m`sk.to_pem()` and `sk.to_der()` will serialize the signing key into the same[0m
[30;1m340 | [0m[35mformats that OpenSSL uses. The PEM file looks like the familiar ASCII-armored[0m
[30;1m341 | [0m[35m`"-----BEGIN EC PRIVATE KEY-----"` base64-encoded format, and the DER format[0m
[30;1m342 | [0m[35mis a shorter binary form of the same data.[0m
[30;1m343 | [0m[35m`SigningKey.from_pem()/.from_der()` will undo this serialization. These[0m

[30;1m89 | [0m[35m## Version-String Flavors[0m
[30;1m90 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m91 | [0m[35mCode which uses Versioneer can learn about its version string at runtime by[0m

[30;1m409 | [0m[35muse NIST256p and SHA256 without their obligating callers to pass[0m
[30;1m410 | [0m[35mhashfunc=sha256 in each time they call sign() or verify().[0m

[30;1m412 | [0m[35m* Release 0.7 (28 Nov 2010)[0m
[30;1m413 | [0m[35m[0m
